fields.title: Infinitive mark
fields.body: 'A' in front of any word makes that word a verb in infinitive form.

fields.title: Words with "Sa+"
fields.body: Sa+gemey; "Sa" in front of a whole word indicates a scientific field. Saying "sa gemey", means the same as we say "Knowledge of numbers". Also, "gemey" is a two part word, "a thing of measure", i.e. a thing with which we measure other things, the most commonly this idea is reflected as a number.
fields.comment: Example of words with "sa+": Samoy - biology (Knowledge of living things); Satonafaw - computer science (Knowledge of computers);

fields.title: Sentence structure
fields.body: Sentences in Mela are structured usually as Subject-Verb-Object.

fields.title: Onomatopoeic words (Similar to sound)
fields.body: Onomatopoeic words are very useful for memorization, hence they are extensively used in Mela. Choice of an onomatopoeic word is dictated by standards of Mela, i.e. easiness of pronunciation, recognizability, also the main characteristics of the chosen word should be widespread among human languages, though it is rarely achievable.
fields.comment: Examples: lagaga - a joke; a toto - to knock; uwa - to slide; keke - to cough; dada - burst; koko - chicken; muwa - a cow; dinidoni - a bell; meme - sheep; tin' - clink; pam' - smack, slap; seysey - rub, scratch; susu - urinate; gugu - defecate; oyka - hiccup; puk' - fart; eyku - burp;  wafa - a dog; igogo - a horse; miw - a cat;

fields.title: Alphabet / Adefa
fields.body:
1-1. Alphabet of Mela is based on Latin script. It consists of 18 letters:

E, T, Y, U, I, O, P, A, S, D, F, G, K, L, V, N, M, W. Also, shwa ' - which is used mostly to separate consonants in borrowed words, pronounced as 'h' in English.

As you can see Mela doesn't use the sounds difficult to pronounce such as Z, R, B etc.

All words avoid two consonants in a row, it makes it very comfortable for people to pronounce, for example the Japanese always end their words with a vowel.

NOTE: Exception is made for words directly borrowed from the natural languages where two consonants in a row are the essential part of such a word. However, those words are beyond first 3,000 and if used they are taken sparingly or for names of globally recognized brands such as Apple, Microsoft, Samsung and similar.
fields.comment:
Adefa de Mela aw leytay no mesew de fasayla li Latine. Se aw kofa de kipaw sewlanila: E, T, Y, U, I, O, P, A, S, D, F, G, K, L, V, N, M, W. Vi pa a saytaw ke Mela ne aw fay e kuy li meyga a lakuy, seli kaw Z, R, B ko mesu li uney.

Toy la aw gofu e di kuylako ye gelaysew, se fa e lakuy e mesu li toylaw. Day gekaw, Iponepe toyve aw neytay e la li gisu foy kuyla.

fields.title: E
fields.body: 'E' in front of any word makes that word an object.
fields.comment: Example: Mi ma e ge li law - "I want a good thing".

fields.title: I
fields.body: 'I' functions as a conjunction between words and sentences. Etymologically derives from Russian 'и', Spanish 'y' and many other languages.
fields.comment: Example: mi i vi va go tu leya - "me and you will go home".

fields.title: "mey"
fields.body:
"-mey" as an ending is used to show measure of some sort if it is added as ending to the subject of measurement.
"mey" is also used for words related to music in that sense that music is measured sound, not just random noise.
fields.comment:
Examples of `-mey` as ending: doyteymey - temperature;  gemey - number; leymey - area; teymey - cost, value; vegamey - age; uneymey - comparison; gamey - size; ukimey - to match; ukimaymey - balance; maymey - weight; gosumey -speed; tomey - a scale; lamey - judgement; nimey - proportion; noymey - height; poymey - depth;

Examples of `mey` in music related words: meykuy - music; meymow - dance;

fields.title: Mu
fields.body: Mu - male, man.
fields.comment: Examples: muleya - husband, muti - boy, lonomu - beard.

fields.title: Proper names and borrowed words.
fields.body:
Proper names and words taken from other languages should be changed according to the phonology of Mela. There are some rules to make it consistent:
  – R = L or Y (Though it can be left as R for recognizability's sake)
  – J in Jonson becomes Y
  – Schwarzenegger – German sound sch becomes S (Swaysnega)
  – Chuck – Ch becomes Sy – Si (Syak)
  – B becomes V, Benedict – Venedit
  – apostrophe (‘) is used to separate three consonants in a row, and two consonants in the end should end with ‘ sound.
  – There are many more sounds in different languages, feel free to make your name sounding according to your own sense of Mela.
  – If there are consonant clusters, a consonant which seems to be more important should be chosen, all others omitted. For example: Justin Timberlake = Yasin Timeleyk, Jennifer Lawrence = Yenifey Lowyens’, or more classic: Dostoevsky = Dostoyewski, Scott Fitzgerald = Skot Fitselayd’.
fields.comment: 1) Names can end on a consonant 2) Names and borrowed words can have two consonants in a row between vowels. For example: Christ – Kilisto, gangster – gang’sta

fields.title: Word orders
fields.body:
There are several word orders in Mela where words come from the same root.
Thus several words are connected semantically, it makes memorization of those words presumably easier.
fields.comment: Examples: Oli - circle, Olu - a hole

fields.title: Words with "taw"
fields.body:
"-taw" as an ending makes words with sense of touching or relating with some feeling to other persons or objects, usually it has an active notion.
"Taw-" in beginning of a word means that subject itself is the object of the feeling.
Look at the examples below to see the difference.
fields.comment:
Examples of active verbs: potaw - to sit; lotaw - to touch; lutaw - to smile; kuytaw - to listen; saytaw - to look;
Examples of reflective verbs: tawneylaw - to suffer; tawlapoy - to be offended; tawga - to be excited; tawmaw - to be pleased

fields.title: Words with "+le"
fields.body: Ending "+le" means result of the action.
fields.comment:
Examples: To listen - "kuytaw" is an act in progress but to hear "kuytawle" is result of the act.
To look - "saytaw" is a process but to see “saytawle” is the result of looking.

fields.title: Numbers - gemey
fields.body:
1 - ki, 2 - di, 3 - pi;
4 - gaw, 5 - faw, 6 - saw, 7 - law, 8 - paw, 9 - naw, 0 - new
10 - kinew / kisuki, 11 - kiki, 12 - kidi. 100 - kisudi, 2000 - disupi.

Numbers are constructed out of ten basic numbers by conjoining them together. Note that it is different from most European languages in a significant way, though very similar to an approach used in American English where they say 'twenty three hundreds' instead of 'two thousands three hundreds'.
However, it is possible to say precisely which number is used by adding a wrapper 'su ... ko', where 'su' + number of zeros in base 10 digits, after that goes 'ko' with the rest of numbers. To differentiate numbers from nouns of the same sound (homonyms) we use “gemey de” in front of  the number, so if you want to say “four” instead of “mountain” you say - “gemey de gaw”.
fields.comment:
Examples: 
100,500 - `ki sudi supi` (two zeros of 100 + three zeros of 1000) `ko faw sudi` (with five hundreds) or `kinewnew ko faw sudi`.
2018 - `dinewkipaw` (simple number, just name basic numbers in a row).
1,000,000 - `ki susaw`
2,123,123 - `di susaw ko kidipi supi ko kidipi`
401,070,006 - `gawnewki susaw lawnew supi ko saw`

fields.title: Oli- as prefix
fields.body: Oli- as prefix is used to indicate circular, but not repetitive action. For example,  'oligo' means 'coming back as happens when you forgot something and coming back to grab it', in contrast 'gogay' is 'come again as if you coming to the same place'. 'Olifa' means to redo, remake vs. 'fagay' to do something again, not necessary from scratch. 'Oli-' mostly replaces 're-' in English.
fields.comment: oligo - come back, olifa - redo, olina - rethink

fields.title: Metals with "-tow" ending
fields.body: Basic word is 'metal' so to make it easier to memorize it copies European word changing only ending - 'metow' = metal. From this root word all other forms can be more easily memorized.
fields.comment: paytow - silver; kitow - iron, first metal in series of ferrum; ditow - steel, second metal in series of ferrum; manitow - coin, metal money; aytow - gold, holy metal; fawtow - copper, electric metal because it is used as the main electrical conductor.

fields.title: "say-": form
fields.body: "say-" in the beginig of words indicates that it is a form.

fields.title: Negation with "Ne"
fields.body:
Modifier "ne" is always in front of the modified word, it has the priority over all other modifiers. It is consistent with such cases as complex sentences such as "gi pa a 'ne' maw ese" - we put "ne" right in front of the verb instead of infinitive modifier "a". Also this pattern is used in many languages such as English.
One colloquial form exists where "ne" and "aw" brought together in "new" - "zero", which is used as negation: "mi new maw" - "I don't like"
fields.comment: Yani aw ne maw - John does not like. Yani du ne maw - John did not like. Yani va ne maw - John will not like.

fields.title: Words that start with a vowel
fields.body:
In word construction those basic words that start with a vowel, such as “oli, uy, ey...”, must come in front of the word. 
But if basic word that logically comes before the “vowel-word “ ends with “w”, it should come first.
As in “dawoluto” - conifer.

fields.title: Welcome to Mela
fields.body:
What is Mela?
Mela is a project of language constructed to be easy to memorize.
It is attained by constructing words as Lego's. Of course, international words are used as well, but they need to be short in order to create new words with them. The idea is that we can know 3 000 words by memorizing only a hundred with +/- roots.

1. The vocabulary is based on the list of the most frequently used words.
 It gives us the opportunity to start speaking the language right away, also it gives us an idea of what words are more important, what are the building blocks of the language. The compound words are understood as separate words, not as a sentence (Mela is not Tokipona). It could be illustrated by Chinese approach, if I say in Chinese 公共汽车 (Gōnggòng qìchē) literally
  it would be “public steam machine” but nobody ever reads it this way, they see only a word for a bus.
The same here in Mela I say "togo" – it is not tool to go, it is a car.
So the basic blocks in the compound words only a tool to MEMORIZE, not a philosophical or etymological description.
 2. Antonyms are created by adding “Ney-“ before modified root, for example – DOY - a day, NeyDOY – night.
 3. Words are selected from the international vocabulary, however if a word doesn’t sound good, another word could be chosen.
Anyway the most basic words become artificial because they consist of the building blocks.
 The vocabulary is not limited by first 3000 words, this number is only the most frequently used words,
  further if there is no way to construct a word from the building blocks, then Mela simply borrows a word which is internationally used the most by changing phonetics according to the Mela rules.
 4. There are some special affixes, they help to make even more words on the basis of already known ones.
 For example, the ending -Le shows the result of an action, for example – SAY – to look at, SAYLE – to see, also MASAY – to look for, MASAYLE – to find.
 I found this beautiful principle in Chinese.
 5. Almost all the words avoid two consonants in a row (except the borrowed words), it makes it very comfortable for people to pronounce.
 Alphabet consist of 18 Latin letters – E, T, Y, U, I, O, P, A, S, D, F, G, K, L, V, N, M, W.
 As you can see Mela doesn’t use the sounds difficult to pronounce such as Z, R, B, and the Slavic – Ж, Ш, Щ, Ц, Ы etc.
 6. Grammar. I think it is very simple as in Tokipona or Glosa.

 No plural ending, as in Chinese just add -su- before the word and voila you have a plural.
 The same with tense, past – du, future – va, present doesn’t have any special mark for pronouns and pointers but has -aw- mark for other words.
 Grammatical mood – would – vu-, imperative – ta.
